                <h2>Conclusion First: Compliance Inspection is the Lifeline of Overseas Advertising</h2>
<p>Many teams treat compliance inspection as a remedial measure after problems occur—this is the biggest misconception. Based on our experience serving numerous overseas enterprises, <strong>80% of account suspension risks actually show warning signals within 48 hours before suspension</strong>, but teams lack standardized inspection procedures, missing the intervention window.</p>
<p>The core value of compliance inspection is not "firefighting after the fact" but "clearing mines in advance." An effective inspection SOP enables operations teams to proactively address issues before they escalate into account-level risks.</p>
<h2>Four Core Nodes of Compliance Inspection</h2>
<h3>Node 1: Account Permissions and Admin Status</h3>
<p>This is the most overlooked yet critical node. Operational experience shows that <strong>admin permission anomalies are a high-frequency precursor to account suspension</strong>. Common scenarios include:</p>
<ul>
<li>New admins added without completing two-factor authentication</li>
<li>Departed employee accounts not removed promptly</li>
<li>Multiple users sharing the same login credentials</li>
</ul>
<p>Recommended action: Perform a permission health check every Monday. Ensure all admin accounts are "active with verification complete" and remove unnecessary accounts promptly. A certain utility app team discovered during inspection that a departed channel partner's account still retained editing permissions three months after leaving—closing it immediately avoided potential account misuse.</p>
<h3>Node 2: Creative Content Compliance Spot Check</h3>
<p>Creatives are the primary review targets of ad systems and direct triggers for compliance violations. During inspection, don't just check "whether there's violating content"—also focus on:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Copy restriction keywords</strong>: Whether expressions involving health claims, financial promises, or private data appear</li>
<li><strong>Material copyright risks</strong>: Whether images, music, or celebrity likenesses are within platform authorization scope</li>
<li><strong>Landing page consistency</strong>: Whether ad creatives and landing page content have exaggerations or contradictions</li>
</ul>
<p>Recommended action: Conduct internal review before each batch of new materials goes live. During inspection, focus on spot-checking materials "online for over 7 days but lacking sufficient conversion data."</p>
<h3>Node 3: Campaign Settings and Targeting Compliance</h3>
<p>Different regions and platforms have varying compliance requirements for targeting settings. During inspection, confirm:</p>
<ul>
<li>Whether audience targeting reaches minors (most platforms explicitly prohibit this)</li>
<li>Whether ads in sensitive categories (finance, healthcare, wellness) have completed prerequisite qualification reviews</li>
<li>Whether scheduling and budget settings comply with platform daily budget limits per account</li>
</ul>
<h3>Node 4: Financial Status and Balance Alerts</h3>
<p>Running out of account balance causes campaign interruption, leading to historical data gaps that affect optimization decisions. More seriously, some platforms implement "quasi-suspension" when balance is insufficient—recovery requires re-passing review after recharge.</p>
<p>Establishing a balance warning mechanism is crucial: Set a <strong>red alert for balance below 3 days' average spend</strong> and a <strong>yellow alert for balance below 7 days' average spend</strong>.</p>
<h2>SOP Implementation Recommendations</h2>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Inspection Frequency</th>
<th>Check Nodes</th>
<th>Assignee</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>Daily</td>
<td>Balance alert status, campaign anomaly alerts</td>
<td>Operations Specialist</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Every Monday</td>
<td>Permission health, creative compliance spot check</td>
<td>Operations Supervisor</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Monthly</td>
<td>Full creative compliance review, qualification document validity</td>
<td>Compliance/Ops Lead</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p>The core logic of this SOP: <strong>High-frequency checks for lightweight nodes, low-frequency checks for heavyweight nodes</strong>. Daily inspection shouldn't become "form-filling theater." Better to do a solid 5-minute daily check than a 30-minute weekly inspection that goes through the motions.</p>
<p>The essence of compliance inspection is transforming "uncertainty" into "manageable risk." Establishing an SOP is not the goal—detecting problems before they escalate is the true value of this mechanism.</p>
